<p class="center small">✒︎  The Tidewater World of Early Virginia  ✒︎</p>

<p>
  Long before Oklahoma, Texas, or the Appalachian mountains entered the family story,
  John’s ancestral path wound along the tidal rivers of Virginia. In the seventeenth and
  eighteenth centuries, the colony of Virginia was dominated by a small group of
  interrelated families who owned land, held office, and shaped the political and religious
  life of the colony. Among them were the Lees, the Ludwells, and the Harrisons—names that
  still appear in American history textbooks, and names that echo quietly in John’s own
  blood.
</p>

<p>
  The Lee family in Virginia grew into a wide network of branches and cousins. Some would
  go on to national prominence, like Richard Henry Lee and Francis Lightfoot Lee, signers
  of the Declaration of Independence, and Henry “Light-Horse Harry” Lee, the Revolutionary
  War officer whose son, Robert E. Lee, became one of the most famous military leaders in
  American history. John’s connection comes through the broader Lee kinship network—less
  famous in the history books, but living in the same world, attending the same churches,
  serving on the same local courts and governing councils.
</p>

