<p>
  The Ludwell family adds another layer to that story. Philip Ludwell and his descendants
  were not only landowners but political figures in colonial Virginia. Members of this
  family held seats on the Governor’s Council and moved between Virginia and London with a
  fluency that speaks to their standing in the British imperial world. One of the Ludwell
  daughters would marry into the Lee family, weaving the two lineages together. From that
  point forward, Lee and Ludwell blood flowed along the same veins.
</p>

<p>
  Through marriage and alliance, the Lee–Ludwell line also became connected to the
  Harrison family, another of the so-called “First Families of Virginia.” The Harrisons
  produced multiple colonial leaders and, eventually, two U.S. presidents: William Henry
  Harrison and Benjamin Harrison. While John’s line does not descend directly from the
  presidential branch, it participates in the same social and familial world. It is part
  of an old, deeply rooted Virginia elite.
</p>

