<p>
  In this Tidewater world, power was anchored in land, in literacy, and in the Church of
  England. The families at the center of that world served as vestrymen in parishes,
  justices in county courts, and members of the House of Burgesses or the Governor’s
  Council. They lived in large houses overlooking rivers and fields, managed enslaved
  labor (a painful but important truth of the era), and navigated the complex loyalties of
  a colony that was both deeply English and distinctly American.
</p>

