<p>
  Over time, this world began to change. Wars, economic shifts, soil exhaustion,
  inheritance patterns, and the expansion of opportunities to the west all began to push
  younger sons and lesser-favored branches of these families away from the Tidewater. The
  eldest sons might inherit a great house and several hundred acres; younger sons might
  inherit a much smaller portion, or be expected to make their own way. For some, that
  meant law, the clergy, or commerce. For others, it meant the frontier.
</p>

<p>
  John’s Lee–Ludwell–Harrison ancestors stand at the edge of that turning point. They
  carry with them the habits of leadership, literacy, and structured life that defined the
  colonial gentry. In the generations to come, those habits would travel west—not as grand
  plantations and political offices, but as quiet forms of dignity, a sense of order, and
  a deep awareness of history and responsibility that would resurface in very different
  settings.
</p>
